{"id": "aby-cecine", "type": "action", "title": "Eyesight filter: worker event stream to summary deposits", "brief": {"why": "The PM must not read full worker transcripts (context exhaustion). An eyesight filter distils each worker's Gueridon event stream into a per-session summary. The PM reads summaries, not transcripts. This is the deposit pattern applied to session monitoring.", "what": "1. Define summary schema: session name, status, key outputs, handoff path, error count 2. Build filter that consumes Gueridon session events and writes summary 3. Define granularity: per-session final summary vs periodic checkpoints 4. PM reads summaries via file deposit pattern", "done": "Worker sessions produce summary deposits. PM reads them without exhausting context. Summary schema is documented and consistent."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-nafola", "order": 7, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:11:52Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — eyesight filter is PM-tier operational tooling"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:41Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-hikifa", "type": "action", "title": "Garde-manger integration for prior work discovery", "brief": {"why": "In this conversation, Sameer had to manually supply the earlier email infrastructure research. An explore reflector should search garde-manger for 'have we explored this before?' and surface relevant prior sessions, preventing re-discovery of settled questions.", "what": "1. Add garde-manger search step to explore-reflector prompt 2. Search patterns: topic keywords, repo names, tool names mentioned in the exploration 3. Surface relevant handoffs and session summaries as context 4. Reflector notes: 'Prior session on [date] concluded [X] — incorporate or revisit?'", "done": "An explore-reflector reviewing a topic we've previously explored finds and cites the prior session. Prior conclusions are incorporated rather than re-derived."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-nafola", "order": 4, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:17:54Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — garde-manger integration is PM-tier"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:40Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-hiwuca", "type": "action", "title": "Pre-compaction memory flush hook", "brief": {"why": "OpenClaw's best pattern: before context compaction, a silent turn fires where the agent saves critical state to external files. This prevents the gradual context erosion that degrades long-running agents. The Agent SDK supports PreCompact hooks.", "what": "1. PreCompact hook in Claude Code settings.json that triggers agent to write current state to handoff file 2. State includes: what was being worked on, what's done, what's blocked, key decisions made 3. Hook fires before CC's internal summarization 4. Handoff file written to standard location (~/.claude/handoffs/) 5. No Agent SDK required — CC hooks work for any spawned claude process", "done": "An agent session that runs long enough to trigger compaction has its critical state preserved in a handoff file. A new session reading that handoff can continue without asking 'what was I doing?'"}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-sumode", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:16:54Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — pre-compaction flush is for long-running PM/worker sessions"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:41Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-jocuce", "type": "action", "title": "Regroup bon outcomes along software architecture boundaries", "brief": {"why": "Current outcomes are grouped by feature/capability (triggers, email, planning). But session efficiency depends on context correlation — Claudes should be able to work an outcome without loading unrelated modules. Outcomes should mirror code boundaries.", "what": "1. Map current src/ modules to functional groups 2. Review existing outcomes against module groups 3. Propose regrouped outcomes that align code and plan 4. Execute regrouping with bon convert/edit", "done": "Each outcome's actions touch at most 2-3 related modules. A Claude can work any outcome without reading the whole codebase."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-kikebu", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T20:53:11Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "done_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:17Z", "done_note": "Executing now — regrouping bons under new architecture-aligned outcomes", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived"}
{"id": "aby-josewe", "type": "action", "title": "Aboyeur CLAUDE.md — goals, routing rules, promotion detection", "brief": {"why": "The aboyeur needs a system prompt that encodes: read bon outcomes (not actions), route triggers as one-shot or PM, detect when a one-shot has created bons (promotion), assign session names, consume minimal context. This is a different document from the PM or worker CLAUDE.md.", "what": "1. Draft aboyeur system prompt with routing rules 2. Goal-reading pattern: bon list --json filtered to outcomes only 3. Promotion detection: monitor for new bons created by one-shots 4. Session naming template injection", "done": "Aboyeur CLAUDE.md exists. An aboyeur Claude can read it cold and correctly route a trigger as one-shot or PM."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-titugu", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:11:22Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "tactical": {"steps": ["Draft aboyeur system prompt with routing rules", "Goal-reading pattern: bon list --json filtered to outcomes", "Promotion detection stub (deferred, but referenced)", "Session naming template"], "current": 4, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-03-15T17:08:10Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z"}
{"id": "aby-jukoho", "type": "action", "title": "Conductor prompt encodes session lifecycle discipline", "brief": {"why": "Daemon-spawned Claudes currently get no guidance on mid-session tactics (context correlation, three questions, wind-down timing). These patterns are proven effective but live only in memory files that workers don't read.", "what": "1. Distill session-lifecycle-patterns.md into conductor system prompt sections 2. Add three-questions checkpoint to worker prompts at natural pauses 3. Add context-correlation hint to conductor's next-action selection", "done": "Conductor prompt includes lifecycle sections. Workers pause for three questions. Conductor picks next work by context overlap."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-nafola", "order": 5, "created_at": "2026-03-06T20:53:02Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:40Z", "done_note": "Subsumed by aby-lizuno (PM CLAUDE.md encodes human-simulator patterns) — same scope, better framing", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z"}
{"id": "aby-kikebu", "type": "outcome", "title": "Multi-session workflow is encoded and self-reinforcing", "brief": {"why": "Session lifecycle patterns are currently tribal knowledge in Sameer's head and memory files. Daemon-spawned Claudes won't inherit discipline unless it's in their prompts and the plan structure mirrors the code.", "what": "1. Encode session lifecycle patterns into conductor/daemon prompts 2. Regroup bons along software architecture boundaries 3. Engineer feedback loops as first-class planning step for each new outcome", "done": "Conductor-spawned Claudes naturally follow session patterns. Bon outcomes map to code modules. New outcomes include feedback loop design."}, "status": "done", "order": 5, "created_at": "2026-03-06T20:52:55Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:52Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived"}
{"id": "aby-kutopu", "type": "action", "title": "Promotion pattern: one-shot escalates to PM when bons are created", "brief": {"why": "A one-shot email conversation can develop into a multi-session project. When the one-shot creates bon actions under an outcome, the aboyeur needs to detect this and spawn a PM to take over. This is the GTD pattern: a next action reveals itself to be a project.", "what": "1. Define the promotion signal (new bons created by a session that started as one-shot) 2. Aboyeur monitors bon state after one-shot completes 3. If new outcome+actions exist, spawn PM scoped to that outcome 4. Hand off the one-shot's session context (handoff file) to the PM", "done": "A one-shot that creates bons triggers PM spawning. The PM picks up from the one-shot's handoff. No manual intervention needed."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-titugu", "order": 4, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:11:45Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — can't test promotion until one-shots actually run"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:40Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-leheta", "type": "action", "title": "Bridge broadcasts session status and availability to mesh peers", "brief": {"why": "Without status, peers cannot tell if a session is busy or available. This causes wasted messages and the human-as-hook problem. Office agents already broadcast fileName and status — CC agents should too. A cleared busy flag with unread inbox messages is a natural daemon trigger.", "what": "1. Poll a working_on file in agent dir — emit status event on change 2. Busy flag file — exists means head-down, absent means available 3. Emit {type: status, fileName: contents, _agent_id: id} on the WebSocket 4. Integrate busy/inbox check as daemon trigger signal", "done": "Peers see what a CC session is working on via get_connected_agents. Busy flag suppresses non-urgent messages. Busy-clear + unread inbox triggers daemon wake."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-dedeju", "order": 4, "created_at": "2026-03-14T18:41:02Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — status broadcasting is operational polish"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:41Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-lizuno", "type": "action", "title": "PM CLAUDE.md encodes human-simulator patterns", "brief": {"why": "The PM needs a system prompt that encodes Sameer's operational patterns: read bon --json for one project, manage the beat (work → review → route), apply context correlation for next-action, ask three questions at checkpoints, wind down at 20-25% context, report progress one-liners to aboyeur. This is the richest of the three CLAUDE.md documents.", "what": "1. Draft PM system prompt with beat pattern 2. Context correlation heuristic section 3. Three questions checkpoint protocol 4. Wind-down and restart-from-bon-state protocol 5. Eyesight filter reading protocol — how PM reads worker summaries", "done": "PM CLAUDE.md exists. A PM Claude can read it cold and manage a sequence of workers/reflectors for one project using bon --json."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-nafola", "order": 6, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:11:30Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — PM CLAUDE.md comes after one-shot loop proves the pattern"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:40Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-lolero", "type": "action", "title": "Decision heuristics for unattended operation", "brief": {"why": "When the human is unavailable, the Aboyeur Claude needs rules for when to proceed vs when to wait. Reversible and cheap = proceed. Irreversible or expensive = HUMAN REVIEW NEEDED. These heuristics encode the judgment calls the human would make.", "what": "1. Decision matrix in shared/prompts/decision-heuristics.md 2. Axes: reversibility (easy/hard/impossible), cost (cheap/moderate/expensive), novelty (proven pattern/new approach), blast radius (local/shared/public) 3. Rules: proceed if reversible+cheap+proven; escalate if any axis is red; default to escalate when uncertain 4. Integration point: reflector prompts reference the heuristics when evaluating 'should we proceed or ask?'", "done": "An Aboyeur reflector facing a reversible cheap decision proceeds without human input. An Aboyeur reflector facing an irreversible decision writes HUMAN REVIEW NEEDED with the specific decision to be made. No false negatives on irreversible decisions in testing."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-titugu", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:17:42Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — heuristics need real routing data to calibrate"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:40Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-mideti", "type": "action", "title": "Add send operation to mise-en-space", "brief": {"why": "The daemon's mise instance needs send capability for claude@planetmodha.com. But this codepath must NEVER exist in the ITV mise installation. Options: git branch that only the daemon deploys from, a feature flag gated by OAuth client identity, or a fork. The separation must be structural (code doesn't exist) not just config (code exists but is disabled).", "what": "1. New tool: tools/send.py wrapping gmail.users.drafts().send() 2. Add 'send' to OPERATIONS frozenset and _DISPATCH dict in server.py 3. This code lives ONLY in the daemon's mise deployment — not in the ITV branch 4. Git strategy: daemon branch of mise-en-space that carries send.py, rebased onto main. Or: mise loads tools from a plugin directory, send.py lives outside the repo. 5. Tests (in daemon branch only)", "done": "mcp__mise__do(operation='send', draft_id='...') sends a draft. Without --allow-send config, the operation returns an error explaining it's disabled. Tests pass."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-poniha", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:17:13Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — send operation is draft-only-first, add send later"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:41Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-nafola", "type": "outcome", "title": "PM Claudes manage multi-session projects as human simulators", "brief": {"why": "The PM Claude is the middle manager — scoped to one project, deep in the weeds, managing the beat pattern (work → review → route). It reads bon state via --json, spawns workers and reflectors via Gueridon bridge, monitors them through filtered event summaries, and applies session lifecycle patterns (context correlation, three questions, drift detection). Disposable — restarts from bon state.", "what": "1. PM CLAUDE.md encodes human-sim patterns (beat, three questions, wind-down) 2. Gueridon bridge integration for spawning/monitoring workers (from aby-pinida) 3. Eyesight filter: worker event stream → per-session summary deposits 4. Context correlation heuristic for next-action selection 5. Explore-phase and planning-phase prompt pairs (from aby-wujime) 6. Garde-manger integration for prior work discovery (from aby-hikifa) 7. Context-pressure reflector trigger (from aby-vaniho)", "done": "PM manages a sequence of 5-10 worker/reflector sessions for one project. Uses bon --json as primary state. Eyesight filter prevents context exhaustion. Reports progress one-liners to aboyeur. Restartable from bon state."}, "status": "done", "order": 8, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:09:44Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:51Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived"}
{"id": "aby-nibifi", "type": "action", "title": "Feedback loop design is a first-class planning step", "brief": {"why": "Tight feedback loops (push-run-log-introspect-rewrite) are the single biggest multiplier for dev velocity. But they're never planned explicitly — they emerge by accident or after friction. Making loop design a standard step when planning new outcomes prevents wasted sessions.", "what": "1. Add feedback-loop-design prompt to planning reflector 2. Template: what's the inner loop, what's the cycle time target, what gates need removing 3. Apply retroactively to current outcomes (what loops exist, what's missing)", "done": "Planning reflector asks about feedback loops. Each outcome has a documented inner loop or explicit note that none is needed."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-kikebu", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-06T20:53:21Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — can't validate feedback loop design until the system runs end-to-end"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:41Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-nisibi", "type": "action", "title": "Document cross-machine collaboration protocol", "brief": {"why": "Today's two-Claude session discovered conventions for working the same codebase from different machines via mesh (push notification before git push, file ownership boundaries, bon action-level only, cross-review protocol). These are only in the mesh transcript — next time this happens, the conventions will be re-derived from scratch.", "what": "1. Write a protocol doc in docs/ covering push/pull sequencing, file ownership to avoid conflicts, bon cross-machine constraints, mesh communication conventions. 2. Reference today's session findings.", "done": "A future two-Claude session can follow the protocol without re-deriving conventions."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-kikebu", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-15T15:42:08Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — cross-machine protocol is premature without a working single-machine loop"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:41Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-pinida", "type": "action", "title": "Conductor spawns workers via Gueridon bridge", "brief": {"why": "The conductor is a human simulator — it does what Sameer does, automated. It needs to spawn and monitor worker Claudes at one remove, the same way Sameer uses Gueridon from his phone. Using spawnAgent() directly makes the conductor a process manager; using Gueridon bridge makes it a session director. Workers stay oblivious to orchestration — they just see a directory, CLAUDE.md, and bons.", "what": "1. Expose Gueridon bridge as MCP tools the conductor can call (spawn session, list sessions, kill session, get session events) 2. Build eyesight filter: stream worker events, deposit per-session summaries (not full transcripts) 3. Conductor reads bon state via bon list --json, picks next action by context correlation 4. Conductor monitors workers via filtered event deposits, asks three questions at checkpoints 5. Structured reflector verdicts (approved/rejected/escalate) route conductor decisions", "done": "Conductor spawns workers via Gueridon bridge API. Worker event stream is filtered to summaries the conductor reads without context exhaustion. Conductor uses bon --json for routing decisions. Reflector verdicts are structured JSON, not just handoff prose."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-nafola", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:16:30Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — PM layer comes after one-shot routing works"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:40Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-poniha", "type": "outcome", "title": "Email flows in and out without human involvement", "brief": {"why": "Email is both the primary trigger (things arrive) and the escalation channel (things need human attention). The daemon polls Gmail, one-shots triage simple emails, PMs handle complex threads. Drafts by default, send only from planetmodha.com deployment. This is the service hatch between the kitchen and the outside world.", "what": "1. Email triage prompt template and thread context (from aby-ravano) 2. Add send operation to mise-en-space (from aby-mideti) 3. Escalation drafts — PM or aboyeur can draft 'needs your attention' emails to Sameer", "done": "Emails trigger appropriate handling (one-shot or PM). Triage produces correct drafts. Send operation exists in daemon deployment only. Escalation emails reach Sameer when needed."}, "status": "done", "order": 10, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:09:59Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:51Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived"}
{"id": "aby-pusomu", "type": "action", "title": "Escalation drafts — aboyeur or PM can email Sameer when stuck", "brief": {"why": "When a PM hits an escalation verdict or the aboyeur detects a stuck PM, the system needs to draft an email to Sameer explaining what happened and what decision is needed. This is the human-in-the-loop escape valve.", "what": "1. Define escalation trigger conditions (reflector escalate verdict, PM stuck, repeated failures) 2. Escalation email template: what happened, what was tried, what decision is needed 3. Wire mise do(operation='draft') into PM and aboyeur escalation paths", "done": "Stuck situations produce a draft email in Sameer's Gmail. The draft includes enough context for Sameer to make a decision without opening a Claude session."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-poniha", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:12:08Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — escalation drafts need working routing first"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:41Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-puvoni", "type": "action", "title": "One-shot vs PM routing logic", "brief": {"why": "The aboyeur's core job is routing: given a trigger, decide whether to spawn a one-shot Claude (single-session, returns summary) or a PM Claude (multi-session, manages a project). Without this logic, every trigger gets the same treatment, wasting PM overhead on simple tasks or under-serving complex ones.", "what": "1. Routing heuristics: does the trigger reference existing bons? Is the email a 'go' signal or a question? 2. One-shot spawn pattern: session name, working dir, prompt template, summary return 3. PM spawn pattern: session name, project dir, PM CLAUDE.md, initial prompt with trigger payload 4. Fallback: if uncertain, spawn one-shot with promotion capability", "done": "Aboyeur correctly routes simple triggers to one-shots and project triggers to PMs. Uncertain triggers default to one-shot with promotion."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-titugu", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:38:31Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived", "tactical": {"steps": ["Routing heuristics function (trigger → one-shot or PM)", "One-shot spawn pattern (session name, prompt, working dir)", "PM spawn pattern stub (deferred but shaped)", "Integration with daemon.ts"], "current": 4, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "done_at": "2026-03-15T17:10:33Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z"}
{"id": "aby-ravano", "type": "action", "title": "Email triage prompt template and thread context", "brief": {"why": "The agent spawned by the Gmail trigger needs a prompt that orients it: who sent the email, what's the thread history, what actions are available (reply draft, escalate, archive, ignore). Thread context across sessions needs per-thread handoff files.", "what": "1. Prompt template: shared/prompts/email-triage.md 2. Classification categories: reply (draft), escalate (notify human), archive (no action), defer (add to reading queue) 3. Per-thread handoff file pattern: handoffs/email/{thread_id}.md 4. Thread context loading: agent reads thread handoff + fetches recent messages via mise 5. Escalation path: write HUMAN REVIEW NEEDED to handoff, daemon notifies via Gueridon push", "done": "An email from a known contact gets a draft reply. An email requesting a decision gets escalated with a notification. A newsletter gets archived with a one-line summary in the thread handoff. All three paths tested."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-poniha", "order": 1, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:17:23Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": null, "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived", "tactical": {"steps": ["Draft email triage prompt template", "Classification categories and routing", "Per-thread handoff pattern", "Escalation path"], "current": 4, "session": "/home/modha/Repos/aboyeur"}, "done_at": "2026-03-15T17:08:45Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z"}
{"id": "aby-titugu", "type": "outcome", "title": "The aboyeur routes triggers with minimal context", "brief": {"why": "The aboyeur is a persistent, minimal-context Claude session that holds goals (bon outcomes) and routes triggers. It decides: one-shot for simple tasks, PM for multi-session projects. It detects promotion — when a one-shot creates bons, it spawns a PM to take over. It sees only summaries and escalations, never project details.", "what": "1. Aboyeur CLAUDE.md — goals, routing rules, promotion detection 2. One-shot vs PM routing logic (rewrite of aby-puvoni) 3. Promotion pattern: one-shot creates bons, aboyeur notices, spawns PM 4. Session naming convention — aboyeur assigns names, all tiers use them 5. Decision heuristics for unattended routing (from aby-lolero)", "done": "Aboyeur runs persistently with minimal context consumption. Routes one-shot and PM correctly. Detects promotion from one-shot to PM. Session names are consistent and self-documenting."}, "status": "done", "order": 7, "created_at": "2026-03-06T22:09:35Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:52Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:54Z", "updated_by": "archived"}
{"id": "aby-vaniho", "type": "action", "title": "Context-pressure reflector trigger", "brief": {"why": "No system has solved context compaction in long-running agents. Agent Teams fails catastrophically. The reflector pattern is the answer: when a worker nears compaction, spawn a reflector to summarize into a handoff, then start a fresh worker. This is compaction-as-review, not compaction-as-loss.", "what": "1. PreCompact hook in Claude Code settings.json (not SDK — CC hooks work for any claude process) 2. Hook writes a sentinel file that the daemon detects 3. Daemon spawns reflector with 'the previous worker is about to lose context — summarize and handoff' prompt 4. Reflector reads worker's partial handoff and recent tool output 5. Reflector writes full handoff with assessment, risks, and next steps 6. Daemon spawns fresh worker hydrated from that handoff", "done": "A worker session that runs long enough to trigger compaction gets a reflector review. The next worker session picks up from the handoff with no context loss. Tested with a deliberately long-running task."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-nafola", "order": 2, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:16:39Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — context-pressure reflector needs a working PM first"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:40Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
{"id": "aby-wujime", "type": "action", "title": "Explore-phase and planning-phase prompt pairs", "brief": {"why": "The explore→plan transition needs worker/reflector prompts for each phase. Explore workers research options; explore reflectors challenge assumptions. Plan workers convert direction to Bons; plan reflectors check Bons against research. These are the prompts that encode what Sameer did in this conversation.", "what": "1. shared/prompts/explore-worker.md — research, build options, sketch architectures 2. shared/prompts/explore-reflector.md — challenge assumptions, walk through data flows, find hidden decisions 3. shared/prompts/plan-worker.md — convert approved direction to Bon outcomes and actions 4. shared/prompts/plan-reflector.md — check Bons against research, verify completeness 5. Phase transition criteria in each reflector prompt", "done": "Running explore-worker then explore-reflector on a new problem produces a clear options summary with challenged assumptions. Running plan-worker then plan-reflector produces well-formed Bons with all three flags populated."}, "status": "done", "parent": "aby-nafola", "order": 3, "created_at": "2026-03-06T19:17:32Z", "created_by": "spm1001", "waiting_for": ["After first loop — explore/plan prompts are PM-tier, not needed for one-shot routing"], "updated_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z", "updated_by": "archived", "done_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:40Z", "archived_at": "2026-04-05T20:13:44Z"}
